{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2feb0138-3a59-4d77-be17-0a484e3c2c5f","content":"## The Problem\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload **bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**. When `JAVA_HOME` points to a different distribution (Temurin), the build uses that instead, which can cause compatibility issues with the Android build tools (d8/r8, aapt2, etc.).\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option 1 — Unset `JAVA_HOME` for MAUI builds** so the workload uses its bundled JDK:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build -f net8.0-android\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Point to the bundled JDK explicitly** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(Home)/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Find and use the workload's JDK:**\n\n```bash\nls ~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/\n# Then set JAVA_HOME to the microsoft_dist_openjdk_17.* path found there\n```\n\n**Option 1 is the simplest** — just unset `JAVA_HOME` before building. The .NET Android workload knows where its own JDK lives and will use it automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"93891d37-56a4-4dce-9a74-c9d02d32f8f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me check if there's a known compatibility issue with .NET MAUI and certain JDK versions/distributions.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution (microsoft-openjdk) rather than other JDK distributions. Actually, let me think more carefully.\n\n.NET MAUI Android builds use JDK 11 or JDK 17 depending on the version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI requires JDK 17. \n\nThe real problem is likely that the .NET Android workload installs its own JDK, but when JAVA_HOME points to Temurin instead, it creates conflicts. On macOS especially, there are often path resolution issues with how the JDK is discovered and used during the build process. Without the specific error message, I'm trying to narrow down the most likely culprit—it's probably a JDK version mismatch, since .NET MAUI 8+ requires JDK 17, or possibly the build picking up the wrong JDK installation on macOS when multiple versions are present. Though I'm second-guessing myself on whether it strictly needs the Microsoft distribution versus any compatible JDK. The real issue is that setting `JAVA_HOME` to Temurin overrides the bundled JDK that comes with the .NET Android workload, causing version incompatibilities with the Android build tools. The solution is to either unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely so the workload uses its own Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, or explicitly configure the project's `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` to point to a compatible JDK version. or point the project configuration to use the bundled JDK instead. I should give them the most practical solution first.","outputTokens":1706,"requestId":"F405:3412D:1F8F479:235D119:69E81A15"},"id":"91abc160-4ed1-4efa-a745-6b7fea043c7d","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:45:41.332Z","parentId":"a0daf97f-3c76-4ee2-9ce3-53b15151721c"}
